correction.p:
Physical condition and scribal interventions (machine-actionable):
(1) damaged/soiled areas affecting text are encoded with damage (optionally @agent/@degree/@extent and @resp="#Xiang", and @corresp to the relevant witness, e.g. #GX);
(2) deletions are encoded with del, using del[@rend="strikethrough"] for struck-through text;
(3) uncertain readings are wrapped in unclear (optionally @reason and @cert);
(4) missing text is encoded with gap, distinguishing gap[@reason="omission"] from gap[@reason="illegible"];
(5) later additions are encoded with add, with @place (margin/above/below/interlinear etc.), and optionally @hand and @resp="#Xiang".
These encodings belong to the transcription layer to preserve manuscript evidence for extraction and alignment.

interpretation.p:
Apparatus conventions: a negative apparatus is used; only GX/ZQ/MY are treated as collated witnesses.
Agreement with the lemma is explicitly encoded on rdg via ana="#agree"; omissions/lacunae use gap (optionally ana="#omitted");
passages outside a witness’s extent are marked ana="#unattested". This explicitness is crucial for machine collation and alignment.
